  markdown:
    To a screen reader, this page appears as a completely empty page. You notice this because your screen reader stops reading aloud after saying something similar to:
    
    > "Empty page - Accessibility Developer Guide. Document. Blank."
    
    This - by the way - is the webpage's `<title>`, the type of the displayed object (<q>Document</q>), and the non-existent content of the displayed object (<q>Blank</q>).
    
    "Why doesn't my screen reader continue reading the stuff I see here on this page?", you may ask.

    Here's the reason: every example page will have a short introductory section on top which is hidden from screen readers. This is done using the `aria-hidden="true"` attribute (which we will learn more about later).

    The whole content you are reading now is in exactly this introductory section.

    You can press `Ctrl + Option + X` anytime to toggle a visual debug mode which shows some information about the accessibility features used in the current example. Try this out now!

